recordDelimiter.help:
This element specifies the record delimiter character when the format is text. The record delimiter is usually a linefeed (
) on UNIX, a carriage return () on MacOS, or both (
) on Windows/DOS. Multiline records are usually delimited with two line ending characters, for example on UNIX it would be two linefeed characters (

). As record delimeters are often non-printing characters, one can use either the special value '
' to represent a linefeed (ASCII 0x0a) and '' to represent a carriage return (ASCII 0x0d). Alternatively, one can use the hex value to represent character values (e.g., 0x0a).

physicalLineDelimiter.help:
This element specifies the physical line delimiter character when the format is text. The line delimiter is usually a linefeed (
) on UNIX, a carriage return () on MacOS, or both (
) on Windows/DOS. Multiline records are usually delimited with two line ending characters, for example on UNIX it would be two linefeed characters (

). As line delimeters are often non-printing characters, one can use either the special value '
' to represent a linefeed (ASCII 0x0a) and '' to represent a carriage return (ASCII 0x0d). Alternatively, one can use the hex value to represent character values (e.g., 0x0a). If this value is not provided, prcessors should assume that the physical line delimiter is the same as the record delimiter.

